summary:
So Mckenna Grace plays chris Evan's niece in Gifted 
AND she plays a young Carol Danvers in Captain Marvel 
So basically captain...
body:
So Mckenna Grace plays chris Evan’s niece in Gifted

AND she plays a young Carol Danvers in Captain Marvel

So basically captain america is captain Marvel’s uncle.

*enter stage left* Headcannon of carol growing up in the 70s looking at these photos of her uncle who died in WW2 and sees the way people react to the photos of this scrawny kid from brooklyn in his ill fitting army uniform when they come to the house. Sees the respect and near revererance in their eyes when they realize who exactly they’re looking at. She wants it. She wants it everytime a boy laughs at her or everytime a classmate smirks and pushes her down. She wants that respect. The day she turns eighteen Carol walks into the recruiters office holding her papers with the same glint in her eye she had everytime she got back up. Only to be told the army doesnt put women on the front lines. Where she’d earn that respect. Taking a deep breath, because this is just one more person shoving her down, she turns to leave and the air force recruiter waves her over telling her about a new initiative that could allow her to not only fight but fly, if shes good enough. The woman behind the counter says it as a challenge and Carol smirks slightly as she fills out the air force paperwork on the spot. Fuck it, any guy can go fight in the army, how many can fly a plane too. She flips the army recruiter off on her way out the door to go pack for basic training.

summary: no offense but i'm blocking anyone that headcanons mcu carol as bi or tries to make mcu carolrhodey a thing. other problematic...
body: no offense but i’m blocking anyone that headcanons mcu carol as bi or tries to make mcu carolrhodey a thing. other problematic aspects aside, how do you watch a film so heavily centered around women, where carol literally comes home to her “best friend” (wife) and daughter, the only people on earth that matter to her, second only to the older woman who inspired her, and think “yeah but she loves men, too!” a film where we’re shown that most of the men in her life have treated her poorly, the man who was her mentor belittled her and used her vulnerabilities for his own personal gain, where her final words to him are “i have nothing to prove to you” and go “yeah but she’s still probably into men!” i just cannot grasp it.
